    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I've been doing a lot of HIIT lately and I keep hearing people talk about \"lactic acid buildup\" and that burning sensation in the muscles. Can you explain the actual biochemistry of how lactic acid is produced during high intensity work and how the body clears it out afterwards?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During intense exercise, when oxygen supply can't keep up with energy demands, your muscles switch to anaerobic metabolism. This process produces pyruvate, which, instead of entering the aerobic cycle, is converted into lactate and hydrogen ions, causing that characteristic burning sensation. After exercise, your body utilizes the Cori cycle, converting lactate back into glucose in the liver, and it also uses lactate as fuel in other tissues, effectively clearing the buildup.",
      "source": "target",
