    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Got it, so the acidity is the real culprit. Does that acidity actually physically damage the muscle tissue during the workout, or is it more like a temporary metabolic disruption that just gets cleaned up later? I'm curious if there's a way to \"outrun\" the buildup or if it's inevitable once you hit that anaerobic threshold.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The acidosis from hydrogen ions is primarily a temporary metabolic disruption that signals fatigue, not necessarily permanent muscle damage during the workout. While prolonged, extreme acidity can inhibit enzyme function, the physiological impact is usually reversible once aerobic recovery begins. There isn't a perfect way to \"outrun\" all buildup, but training smarter around your lactate threshold allows you to sustain higher intensities for longer durations.",
      "source": "target",
